title Nock lap 2 -- the macro layer, proven equal to lap 1's primitives
prompt kg
think Followed my own last recommendation directly: a Nock lap 2 (opcodes 6-11, already scoped in the original phased plan) as the natural next step in this same shape. Re-derived each opcode's reduction rule by hand before writing a line of code, working from the real spec definitions rather than memory alone.
think Scoped the lap honestly rather than attempting all six remaining opcodes at once: 6, 7, 8, 9, and 11 are each expressible by direct composition of primitives lap 1 already proved (opcode 2, opcode 0, and autocons); opcode 10 (edit -- the constructive counterpart to slot addressing, splicing a new value into a tree at an address) needs a genuinely new primitive this tree has not built, so it stays honestly unimplemented rather than rushed. Named this split plainly in the module doc comment and README rather than letting "lap 2" quietly mean "lap 2 except one op I skipped."
think Derived pure 0-5 expansions for opcodes 7, 8, and 9 by hand, checking each against the official identity: *[a 7 b c] = *[a 2 b [1 c]]; *[a 8 b c] = *[a 2 [b [0 1]] [1 c]] (autocons carrying [*[a b] a] as the extended subject); *[a 9 b c] = *[X 2 [0 1] [0 b]] where X = *[a c] is the core, shared rather than recomputed. Verified each derivation symbolically before writing any fixture, then let the actual run confirm it.
think Implemented each opcode natively in nock_core.rye's own eval() switch (fast, direct, readable) rather than having the interpreter literally re-derive its own macro expansions at every call -- the expansions exist to be proven equal, in the witness, not to be the production code path. This matches how a real macro/sugar layer is supposed to work: a faster spelling of something already provably equivalent.
think Wrote nock_lap2_witness.rye to prove each opcode twice -- once native, once via the hand-built expansion, asserted equal -- exactly the phased plan's own stated test ("proving it reduces to the same result as its stated 0-5 expansion"), rather than testing only the native behavior and calling the expansion argument sufficient.
think Two real bugs caught by the build and one caught by re-reading my own prior witness rather than assuming it still held: `test` is a reserved word in this pinned Zig, renamed to test_result; and critically, lap 1's own existing witness had used opcode 6 to prove "unimplemented opcode refuses cleanly" -- true when written, false the moment opcode 6 became real, and it crashed with a raw panic rather than a clean NockError the instant I rebuilt it. Fixed the stale fixture to use opcode 10 instead (still genuinely unimplemented) before treating lap 1 as still green -- docs-and-implementation-sync applied to a witness's own fixture, not only to prose.
think Hand-derived opcode 6's own four-nested-star expansion (*[a 4 4 b] doubly-increments a boolean into a validated slot address; *[[2 3] 0 ...] validates it; *[[c d] 0 ...] selects the matching branch as data; a final *[a ...] evaluates the selected branch against the original subject) and reconstructed it literally in the witness, step by step, rather than trusting the derivation without running it.
think Caught a real transcription bug the hard way, three attempts in: quoting opcode 6's spec formula in the module README, I dropped the outer *[a ...] wrapper without removing its matching closing bracket, leaving one unbalanced ]. Retyped the fix twice more by hand and got it wrong both times before stopping and using a small script to extract and compare against the exact string in old/doc/spec/nock/4.txt (the real spec, held whole in this fork's own tree) rather than continuing to eyeball brackets. Worth naming plainly: three manual attempts at a bracket count all failed; the fourth, done by a script against a verified source, succeeded on the first try.
think Cross-built both nock_core.rye's extended eval() and the new lap-2 witness for riscv64 and confirmed byte-identical output before folding lap 2 into tools/glow_riscv_target_witness.rish as the seventh keystone piece, keeping this session's own running practice of proving new code on the same substrate as its elder vanes rather than leaving it as a separate claim.
obs This turn's most valuable lesson may be procedural rather than architectural: when a manual transcription check fails once, the right move is not to retry manually a second and third time -- it is to reach for a script and a verified source immediately. I did this only on the fourth attempt; naming it here so the next similar moment reaches for the script first.
